m cells are introduced and the important players involved in regeneration such as oval cells, bone marrow and stellate cells are reviewed. The cell signaling pathways that initiate liver regeneration and regulate the switch between proliferation and apoptosis are presented and the role of liver stem cells in tumorigenesis is discussed. The book also treats the epigenetic regulation of liver stem cells and the roles of inflammation and angiogenesis in liver regeneration. This compact overview of the fascinating regenerative capacity of the liver will be of interest to graduate students and post-docs in molecular biology, biochemistry and medicine.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aLiverxDiseases. 0aLiverxRegeneration. 0aStem cells. 4aBiochemie. 4aLeber. 4aMolekularbiologie. 4aRegeneration. 4aTherapie. 7aMEDICAL / Internal Medicine.2bisacsh  aBiochemistry.  aLiver.  aMolecular Biology.  aRegeneration.  aTherapy.1 aBode, Johannes G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuschmann, Tobias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChoi, Steve S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeFrances, Marie C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiehl, Anna Mae, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrasdo, Dirk, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEglinger, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEsch, Jan Schulte am, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFürst, Günter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGasbarrini, Antonio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGebhardt, Rolf, econtributor.4ctb4